{"caption": "Jeeves passed away at 5 minutes after noon today, Saturday the 15th of January.His breathing had become laboured  Sashe and I agreed that letting him go was more humane than have him struggle for who knows how many more hours or days.Our vet was as kind and compassionate as always  we held Jeeves as he breathed his last and told him that he will be cherished beyond measure.And with a final sigh, Jeeves slipped into what has always been his favourite pastime  sleep.Thank you all for so many messages of care and concern  I know how much you loved him. I am so grateful to all who kept him, Dash, Sashe and I in your thoughts.Jeeves was gentle and tender and warm. He had a fondness for being looked after and so willingly submitted to being cared for. I need to remember this now, at a time where the grief is attacking my body in suffocating waves, because I cannot hold myself up through the pain.I also cannot take a deep enough breath yet, but when I do, it will honour Jeeves’ extraordinary determination to draw affection to himself and return it manifold to everyone around him.I have to remind myself that sixteen and a half is a life well lived for a dog, and for a rescued dog at that. When we found Jeeves more than six years ago we knew that we had an uncertain time ahead because he was already in such bad shape from neglect. And we didn’t expect him to be around for very long because of his underlying health conditions. But Jeeves surprised us all with his unshakable will to live and thrive. What was his secret you might ask? Love fiercely and trust wholly. That was, and will always be our Jeeves 💜", "username": "sareesandstories", "number_of_comments": "432"}

{"caption": "Yesterday was the first time in 5 weeks that I actually felt like documenting my #sareeofthedayI picked a vintage printed affair that belonged to my grandmother to wear for a tv production meeting which went better than I could have hoped for. The Saree stayed put through lunch prep and a short nap too! My final meeting of the day was for the British Council #ConnectionsThroughCulture grant project that I’m working on  I have an update for you on this.All three of us collaborating have dealt with challenging circumstances in the past few months  despite it all we met regularly and worked on shaping our project. But there always has been room to breathe, even if the request was in the last moment. I am filled with gratitude for Abhi and Dhinesha  the safe space they built has gently allowed the broken me to find the will to write again.Sarees and Secrets was due to be staged at the end of January but has been post-poned to Saturday the 26th of February at 8pm (Malaysian Time). It will be streamed online and I’ll share those details soon as well as how an international audience can interact with the experience. Yes, you get to be a part of it too!Last Wednesday, we began our session with our usual check in. Abhi and Dhinesha asked how Jeeves was doing  I shared that the end was likely close. I also told them the story of how Sashe and I rescued Jeeves  he was abandoned at the age of 10 outside an animal shelter by a breeder because he had outlived his usefulness. It’s an origins story that never loses its horror  then Abhi did something that floored me. Through our 2 hour meet ups, we throw writing prompts into the session and create individual snippets over 10 minute time limits. There are no rules except that the word or phrase must be incorporated in some way in the piece. These exercises flex writing muscles  sometimes we each get the same prompt, or it is different for everyone. Last week, Abhi found herself with this random prompt: Would anybody even want it? Swipe through to read what she came up with in 10 minutes  I’m sharing this with permission. Thank you again @abeeabuzz 💜#onewomanshow #playwright  #sareesandsecrets #britishcouncilctc", "username": "sareesandstories", "number_of_comments": "26"}
